body:
## Summary

JS `--capture api` produces **invalid GFM tables** when a Google Docs cell contains multiple paragraphs. Rust handles the same input correctly. After issue #108 was resolved, this is the last remaining markdown-quality regression I can find on either CLI.

## Versions

| | tested | result |
|---|---|---|
| `@link-assistant/web-capture` | **1.7.18** (latest) | ❌ broken |
| `web-capture` (cargo) | **0.3.10** (latest) | ✅ clean |

(Re-tested after #108 closure — all the browser-mode list/blockquote bugs from #108 are now fixed in both engines. This issue is independent.)

## Repro

Any Google Doc with a table where a cell contains 2+ paragraphs separated by blank lines. The exact HTML that the public `/export?format=html` endpoint serves for such a cell looks like:

```html
<td>
  <p>First paragraph.</p>
  <p>Second paragraph.</p>
  <p>Third paragraph.</p>
</td>
```

### Expected (and what Rust 0.3.10 produces)

```md
| First paragraph.<br/><br/>Second paragraph.<br/><br/>Third paragraph. | … |
```

The `<br/><br/>` keeps the cell on a single physical line. GFM tables require this — any blank line inside a cell terminates the table.

### Actual (JS 1.7.18)

```md
| First paragraph.  

Second paragraph.  

Third paragraph.  
 | … |
```

Each paragraph on its own line, separated by trailing-double-space hard breaks and bare blank lines. **GitHub-flavored Markdown renders this as a 1-row table followed by stray paragraphs**, not a multi-row table — every subsequent row is dropped.

## Root cause

In `js/src/gdocs-preprocess.js`, `inlineTableCellHtml` flattens `<p>` children into the parent `<td>` and joins them with a single `<br>`:

https://github.com/link-assistant/web-capture/blob/main/js/src/gdocs-preprocess.js#L362-L383

```js
function inlineTableCellHtml($, cell) {
  const parts = [];
  $(cell).contents().each(function () {
    if (this.type === 'tag' && ['p', 'div'].includes(this.tagName)) {
      const inner = $(this).html() || '';
      if (inner.trim()) parts.push(inner);
      return;
    }
    …
  });
  return parts.join('<br>');     // ← bug
}
```

The downstream html-to-markdown converter (`turndown` or similar) renders a single `<br>` as a hard-break (two trailing spaces + newline). When a Markdown table cell hits a real newline, GFM ends the table.

## Suggested fix

Change line 382 to `parts.join('<br><br>')`. That matches what Rust emits and renders correctly in every GFM renderer.

```diff
-  return parts.join('<br>');
+  return parts.join('<br><br>');
```

## Suggested unit test

```js
// js/tests/unit/gdocs-preprocess.test.js
test('inlineTableCellHtml joins multiple <p> with <br><br> for valid GFM', () => {
  const input = '<table><tr><td><p>A</p><p>B</p><p>C</p></td><td>x</td></tr></table>';
  const { html } = preprocessGoogleDocsExportHtml(input);
  // Cell should be one logical line — check that <br><br> is present and there
  // are no remaining <p> tags inside the <td>.
  expect(html).toContain('A<br><br>B<br><br>C');
  expect(html).not.toMatch(/<td[^>]*>[^<]*<p/);
});
```

## Why this matters

Tables with multi-paragraph cells are common in real-world Google Docs (FAQ-style content, translation matrices, anything with multi-language explanations). Currently any such doc round-tripped through JS api-mode produces broken markdown that no GFM renderer (GitHub, GitLab, mkdocs, pandoc, comrak, marked) will display correctly.

## Engine parity check

Rust 0.3.10 has been correct since at least 0.3.9 — its preprocessor uses the equivalent of `<br/><br/>`. The JS port simply diverged. Aligning the two CLIs on `<br><br>` makes them match.
